00:11:37.560 --> 00:11:39.680
So, then we might ask, and
this is the third ingredient,

00:11:39.680 --> 00:11:41.080
well, where's public housing?

00:11:41.080 --> 00:11:43.910
Or housing assistance of any kind?

00:11:43.910 --> 00:11:48.360
And the answer is it's there but
it's only for the lucky minority

00:11:48.360 --> 00:11:50.250
of families that receive it today.

00:11:50.250 --> 00:11:52.430
So, only about six percent
of poor families that live

00:11:52.430 --> 00:11:55.880
in public housing today, that's
that little blue part of the pie,

00:11:55.880 --> 00:11:59.120
12 percent receive a
rent reducing voucher,

00:11:59.120 --> 00:12:01.360
which used to be called
section eight vouchers.

00:12:01.360 --> 00:12:04.770
But the unlucky majority, the
remaining 75 percent receive --

00:12:04.770 --> 00:12:07.810
what's the technical term.

00:12:07.810 --> 00:12:13.260
Nothing. Nada, Zippo from state,
local or federal governments.

00:12:13.260 --> 00:12:14.580
You know, I think that's
be a situation

00:12:14.580 --> 00:12:16.960
that would be utterly
unthinkable when it comes

00:12:16.960 --> 00:12:18.570
to meaning other basic needs.

00:12:18.570 --> 00:12:20.550
Imagine if we turned away
three and four families

00:12:20.550 --> 00:12:21.850
that apply for food stamps.

00:12:21.850 --> 00:12:23.260
Like, "I'm sorry, we
don't have enough for you.

00:12:23.260 --> 00:12:24.780
You have to go hungry."

00:12:24.780 --> 00:12:27.860
But that's exactly how we treat
low income families searching

00:12:27.860 --> 00:12:29.800
for affordable shelter today.

00:12:29.800 --> 00:12:34.600
So, Arlene looked up looking for
housing assistance a long time ago.

00:12:34.600 --> 00:12:37.130
One day on a whim she stopped by
the housing authority and asked

00:12:37.130 --> 00:12:39.000
about the list and she was told

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:42.170
by the person behind the glass
like, "The list is frozen."

00:12:42.170 --> 00:12:45.480
Because on it were 3,500
families who had applied

00:12:45.480 --> 00:12:48.280
for rent assistance five years ago.

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:49.580
And that's not bad.

00:12:49.580 --> 00:12:52.630
I mean, the waiting for
public housing in some

00:12:52.630 --> 00:12:56.380
of our big cities has not counted
in years, it's counted in decades.

00:12:56.380 --> 00:13:00.610
So, I have two young
children now and if I apply

00:13:00.610 --> 00:13:01.910
for public housing today

00:13:01.910 --> 00:13:05.160
in this city I would
probably be a grandfather

00:13:05.160 --> 00:13:08.040
by the time my application
came up for review.

00:13:08.040 --> 00:13:10.980
So, if Arlene wanted public housing
this is what she'd have to do.

00:13:10.980 --> 00:13:13.730
She'd have to wait three or four
years before the list unfroze

00:13:13.730 --> 00:13:16.210
and then she'd have to wait
another five or six year

00:13:16.210 --> 00:13:18.510
until her name made it
to the top of the pile.

00:13:18.510 --> 00:13:21.710
And then she'd just have to pray

00:13:21.710 --> 00:13:24.820
that the person reviewing her
application would ignore all the

00:13:24.820 --> 00:13:26.880 position:56%
evictions she collected while trying

00:13:26.880 --> 00:13:29.690
to make ends meet unassisted
in the private market.

00:13:29.690 --> 00:13:32.610
When we think of the typical poor
family today, we shouldn't think

00:13:32.610 --> 00:13:35.140
of them living in public
housing or getting any kind

00:13:35.140 --> 00:13:36.690
of help from the government.

00:13:36.690 --> 00:13:39.920
We should think of Arlene
because she's the average case.

00:13:39.920 --> 00:13:45.600
So, on 13th street, Arlene found
this bucket of paint and rollers

00:13:45.600 --> 00:13:48.690
and brushes in the basement and
she gave the walls a fresh coat

00:13:48.690 --> 00:13:52.630
but not long after moving in
her sister died and she pitched

00:13:52.630 --> 00:13:55.000
in some money for the funeral.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:57.510
She didn't have the money
but no one else did either

00:13:57.510 --> 00:14:00.030
and she gave out of love.

00:14:00.030 --> 00:14:02.200
The next month she
missed an appointment

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:03.750
with her welfare case worker

00:14:03.750 --> 00:14:06.340
because the letter announcing
the appointment was mailed

00:14:06.340 --> 00:14:10.200
to 19th street or maybe
Atkinson Avenue.

00:14:10.200 --> 00:14:12.670
And Arlene's case worker
tried sending in the computer

00:14:12.670 --> 00:14:17.660
and Arlene's $620 a month check was
cut, we call it getting sanctioned,

00:14:17.660 --> 00:14:20.410
and by that time she fell
two months behind on rent

00:14:20.410 --> 00:14:22.340
and she got the pink papers.

00:14:22.340 --> 00:14:27.130
So, Milwaukee is a city of
about 105,000 renter homes.

00:14:27.130 --> 00:14:30.770
Every year in Milwaukee landlords
evict about 16,000 people.

00:14:30.770 --> 00:14:34.740
That's about 40 people a
day evicted in Milwaukee.

00:14:34.740 --> 00:14:37.550
We've know crunched the numbers
in Cleveland, in Kansas City,

00:14:37.550 --> 00:14:40.770
in Chicago, we found rates
similar to Milwaukee's.

00:14:40.770 --> 00:14:45.170
New York city you see 60 marshal
evictions every single day.

00:14:45.170 --> 00:14:46.470
It's estimated that renters

00:14:46.470 --> 00:14:49.960
in over 2.8 million homes
think they'll be evicted soon.

00:14:49.960 --> 00:14:52.980 position:56%
Now, the first time I crunched these
numbers I thought they're wrong

00:14:52.980 --> 00:14:54.290
because they are so high.

00:14:54.290 --> 00:14:58.300
They're wicked scary,
as we say in Boston.

00:14:58.300 --> 00:15:02.210
But these numbers only count
formal court ordered evictions

00:15:02.210 --> 00:15:04.780
and there are other ways,
cheaper and quicker ways

00:15:04.780 --> 00:15:06.560
for a landlord to get you out.

00:15:06.560 --> 00:15:09.310
So, Joe Prozinski, he was a
building manager in the inner city,

00:15:09.310 --> 00:15:11.940
and he said, "You know, Matt,
for every eviction I do that goes

00:15:11.940 --> 00:15:14.020
to the court, there are
like 10 that don't."

00:15:14.020 --> 00:15:18.050
So, what Joe would do is say
like, "Look, Carlos, you know,

00:15:18.050 --> 00:15:20.110
you're behind, man, and
I just I need my money.

00:15:20.110 --> 00:15:21.910
I'll tell you what.

00:15:21.910 --> 00:15:25.740 position:56%
I'll give you $200 and I'll let you
use my van if you're out by Sunday."

00:15:25.740 --> 00:15:28.700
So, if you got to get evicted,
that's not a bad eviction.

00:15:28.700 --> 00:15:30.350
I met another landlord
that if you're behind,

00:15:30.350 --> 00:15:31.990
he'll just take your door off.

00:15:31.990 --> 00:15:35.100 position:56%
There are a lot of ways to get a
family out and we worked really hard

00:15:35.100 --> 00:15:38.040
in that survey to capture
all those informal eviction

00:15:38.040 --> 00:15:39.340
that never go through the court.

00:15:39.340 --> 00:15:42.950 position:56%
And if you had those up with formal
evictions that are legally processed

00:15:42.950 --> 00:15:45.080
and if you count things
like building condemnations,

00:15:45.080 --> 00:15:48.260
like what happened to
Arlene's place on 19th street

00:15:48.260 --> 00:15:53.150 position:56%
and landlord foreclosures, you learn
that every two years in Milwaukee,

00:15:53.150 --> 00:15:57.970
one in eight renters is
evicted, which is crazy.

00:15:57.970 --> 00:15:59.270
One in eight.

00:15:59.270 --> 00:16:01.200
Not one in eight single moms, not
one in eight folks in deep poverty,

00:16:01.200 --> 00:16:05.500
just one in eight renters
every eight -- every two years.

00:16:05.500 --> 00:16:08.940
And like poverty researchers
and journalists like me,

00:16:08.940 --> 00:16:12.000
like for a long time we've
written sentences like this.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:16.690
"Low income families exhibit high
rates of residential insecurity."

00:16:16.690 --> 00:16:19.930
And we haven't said why and I
think what we're learning is

00:16:19.930 --> 00:16:23.230
that poor folks are moving so
much because they're forced to.

00:16:23.230 --> 00:16:25.060
And it's not just a
rhetorical point, you know,

00:16:25.060 --> 00:16:27.490
we have a statistical model
that shows that if you control

00:16:27.490 --> 00:16:31.260
for evictions, low income families
don't move more than anyone else,

00:16:31.260 --> 00:16:33.820
which means if we want
more family stability

00:16:33.820 --> 00:16:37.580
and we want more community
stability we need fewer evictions.

00:16:37.580 --> 00:16:41.000
This is a problem that affects
the young and the old, the sick

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:42.350
and the able bodied, but the face

00:16:42.350 --> 00:16:45.580
of our eviction epidemic
is just moms with kids.

00:16:45.580 --> 00:16:47.960
Moms with kids, if you go
into any urban housing court

00:16:47.960 --> 00:16:51.610
around the country you just see
like a ton of kids sitting there.

00:16:51.610 --> 00:16:55.180 position:56%
Until recently the south Bronx, it's
housing court had a daycare inside

00:16:55.180 --> 00:16:58.460
of it because there were so many
kids coming through its stores.

00:16:58.460 --> 00:17:01.550
And low income African American
women like Arlene and moms

00:17:01.550 --> 00:17:05.550
in particular are evicted
at startlingly high rates.

00:17:05.550 --> 00:17:07.220
Among Milwaukee renters, one

00:17:07.220 --> 00:17:10.500
in five black women report
being evicted sometime

00:17:10.500 --> 00:17:14.010
in their life compared
to one in 15 white women.

00:17:14.010 --> 00:17:16.710
And I think that should trouble us.

00:17:16.710 --> 00:17:18.950
I think that should
disturb us because it means

00:17:18.950 --> 00:17:21.490
that eviction is something
like the feminine equivalent

00:17:21.490 --> 00:17:23.210
to incarceration.

00:17:23.210 --> 00:17:24.540
Now, we know that many of our poor,

00:17:24.540 --> 00:17:27.690
young African American men are
being swept out by the long arm

00:17:27.690 --> 00:17:29.170
of the criminal justice system.

00:17:29.170 --> 00:17:30.990
They're being locked up.

00:17:30.990 --> 00:17:33.330
Many of our poor African-American
women are being locked out

00:17:33.330 --> 00:17:35.150
and they're disproportionately
bearing the brunt

00:17:35.150 --> 00:17:37.730
of the eviction crisis.

00:17:37.730 --> 00:17:41.310 position:56%
This also isn't just a crisis that's
on the north side of Milwaukee

00:17:41.310 --> 00:17:42.610
or the south side of Chicago.

00:17:42.610 --> 00:17:44.550
This is in poor white communities
which I write about a lot

00:17:44.550 --> 00:17:47.060
in my books and Latino
and immigrant communities.

00:17:47.060 --> 00:17:50.090
It's in expensive cities like this
one and it's in inexpensive cities

00:17:50.090 --> 00:17:51.790
like Milwaukee and
Baltimore and Huston.

00:17:51.790 --> 00:17:55.370
One in five of all renters in
America now spends over 50 percent

00:17:55.370 --> 00:17:57.200
of their income on housing.

00:17:57.200 --> 00:18:03.570 position:56%
So, Arlene went to eviction court
and as is court custom in Milwaukee,

00:18:03.570 --> 00:18:07.040
she got to stay two extra
days in her apartment for each

00:18:07.040 --> 00:18:10.170 position:56%
of her two days, and those days came
and went and she was ordered to be

00:18:10.170 --> 00:18:12.820
out on a day in early January.

00:18:12.820 --> 00:18:16.960
My Milwaukee friends here will tell
you January is cold in Milwaukee

00:18:16.960 --> 00:18:19.350
and this January was
especially cold.

00:18:19.350 --> 00:18:23.820
The weather men had said it would
drop below 40 with the wind chill.

00:18:23.820 --> 00:18:26.790
But if Arlene waited
any longer, you know,

00:18:26.790 --> 00:18:30.300
the landlord would call the sheriff
and he would arrive within 10 days

00:18:30.300 --> 00:18:34.390
with a judge's order and a
side arm and a team of movers

00:18:34.390 --> 00:18:36.370
and they would have piled
everything on the side walk.

00:18:36.370 --> 00:18:39.180
And they take everything, like
the meat cuts in the freezer,

00:18:39.180 --> 00:18:40.870
the shower curtains, the bible,

00:18:40.870 --> 00:18:43.450
the silk plants, Jarafis'
asthma machine.

00:18:43.450 --> 00:18:48.800
And so, Arlene just struck out into
the cold and after a lot of calls,

00:18:48.800 --> 00:18:53.700 position:56%
you know, she finally found domestic
violence shelter room 30 minutes

00:18:53.700 --> 00:18:55.000
away from Milwaukee.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:59.400
She just lied about being abused
so she could get her boys a roof

00:18:59.400 --> 00:19:02.180
and she was once again on the
hunt for another place to live.

00:19:02.180 --> 00:19:09.220
So, she called on or applied
to 20 apartments, and then 40,

00:19:09.220 --> 00:19:13.700
and then 60, and then 80.

00:19:13.700 --> 00:19:15.000
I counted.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:17.890
She was accepted to none of them.

00:19:17.890 --> 00:19:20.670
Even in the inner city
many were out of reach.

00:19:20.670 --> 00:19:21.970
And the place she could afford,

00:19:21.970 --> 00:19:24.740
if she basically tossed
everything she had at the rent,

00:19:24.740 --> 00:19:26.040
weren't calling back either.

00:19:26.040 --> 00:19:29.870
And part of the reason, besides her
poverty, was her eviction record.

00:19:29.870 --> 00:19:33.290 position:56%
So, in Milwaukee your eviction is
published publicly online for anyone

00:19:33.290 --> 00:19:38.820
to see and if it's not in your
city there are literally hundreds

00:19:38.820 --> 00:19:40.210
of tenant screening
companies waiting

00:19:40.210 --> 00:19:41.900
to sell landlords this information.

00:19:41.900 --> 00:19:44.090 position:56%
And this is a big deal to landlords.

00:19:44.090 --> 00:19:46.040
You know, most land lords
that I spent time with said,

00:19:46.040 --> 00:19:48.080
"We're not going to take
anyone with an eviction

00:19:48.080 --> 00:19:50.040 position:56%
within the last two or three years."

00:19:50.040 --> 00:19:51.870
So, this mark, this
blemish of eviction

00:19:51.870 --> 00:19:55.740
that follows families is the reason
they are forced into worse housing

00:19:55.740 --> 00:20:00.590
and into worse neighborhoods
after they're evicted.

00:20:00.590 --> 00:20:05.250
So finally at the 90th
landlord, Mr. 90 said yes.

00:20:05.250 --> 00:20:09.360
He had a one-bedroom
apartment, it was $525.

00:20:09.360 --> 00:20:12.580
Arlene didn't much consider,
like, the conditions of the place,

00:20:12.580 --> 00:20:13.880
what the neighborhood was like.

00:20:13.880 --> 00:20:16.430
"A house is a house,"
she told Story.

00:20:16.430 --> 00:20:21.420
So two months after their eviction
court hearing, they moved in.

00:20:21.420 --> 00:20:22.720
And Arlene liked it.

00:20:22.720 --> 00:20:25.980
You know, all the lights worked,
all the cabinets had fixtures.

00:20:25.980 --> 00:20:30.290
And when she and the boys had
unloaded a bunch of the stuff,

00:20:30.290 --> 00:20:33.300
Arlene just like sat down
on the floor and she found

00:20:33.300 --> 00:20:38.020
like a trash bag full of
towels and leaned against it.

00:20:38.020 --> 00:20:42.010
And Story came over and, like,
pitched his 14-year-old head

00:20:42.010 --> 00:20:47.220
into her shoulder, and Jafaris came
and like snuggled into her lap,

00:20:47.220 --> 00:20:52.670
and they just stayed like
that for a long time.

00:20:52.670 --> 00:20:54.760
So Arlene got her stuff
out of storage.

00:20:54.760 --> 00:20:56.730
She hung pictures on the wall.

00:20:56.730 --> 00:20:58.670
She hung a sign over the
sink to Story that said,

00:20:58.670 --> 00:21:01.240
"If you do not clean
up after yourself,

00:21:01.240 --> 00:21:03.010
we are going to have problems."

00:21:03.010 --> 00:21:09.150
Do you guys remember
what it's like to 14?

00:21:09.150 --> 00:21:10.540
Sucky and brutal.

00:21:10.540 --> 00:21:13.480
And it's especially hard to be 14

00:21:13.480 --> 00:21:16.220
and experience long
stretches of homelessness.

00:21:16.220 --> 00:21:20.010
Between 7th and 8th grade, Story
went to five different schools.

00:21:20.010 --> 00:21:24.020
And at his new school, he
started acting out a little bit,

00:21:24.020 --> 00:21:25.900 position:56%
and one day a teacher yelled at him.

00:21:25.900 --> 00:21:30.120
And he got mad and he kicked
her in the shin and he ran home.

00:21:30.120 --> 00:21:31.480 position:56%
And the teacher called the principal

00:21:31.480 --> 00:21:34.780
but then she thought it would be
appropriate to call the police,

00:21:34.780 --> 00:21:38.050
and when officers visited Arlene
and her boys at the new apartment,

00:21:38.050 --> 00:21:44.250
and the landlord found out about
that, he told her she had to go.

00:21:44.250 --> 00:21:45.550
It's kids.

00:21:45.550 --> 00:21:48.610
You know, kids are a
big part of this story.

00:21:48.610 --> 00:21:51.190
They can prolong the time you're
homeless after your eviction,

00:21:51.190 --> 00:21:54.330
and they sometimes are the
reason for your eviction.

00:21:54.330 --> 00:21:57.310 position:56%
In fact, when we look at that
survey that we did in housing court,

00:21:57.310 --> 00:21:58.820
that survey where we
were trying understand,

00:21:58.820 --> 00:22:01.150
"Why is it that you get
evicted but you don't,

00:22:01.150 --> 00:22:03.040
even though you owe your
landlord the same thing?"

00:22:03.040 --> 00:22:06.520
What we found was it wasn't
race, it wasn't gender,

00:22:06.520 --> 00:22:07.950
it wasn't even how much you owed.

00:22:07.950 --> 00:22:09.500
It was kids.

00:22:09.500 --> 00:22:11.300
If you lived with children,

00:22:11.300 --> 00:22:13.260
the chance of you getting
evicted tripled [inaudible].

00:22:13.260 --> 00:22:16.780
What you're seeing in that
finding is landlord discretion.

00:22:16.780 --> 00:22:18.080
You're seeing the landlord say,

00:22:18.080 --> 00:22:21.180
"I'll work with you
but not with you."

00:22:21.180 --> 00:22:27.400 position:56%
Because, you know, like, kids, like,
use the curtains for superhero capes

00:22:27.400 --> 00:22:29.570 position:56%
and they flush toys down the toilet.

00:22:29.570 --> 00:22:31.440
They cause some guy whose
car's just been smacked

00:22:31.440 --> 00:22:34.000
with a snowball to
kick your door in.

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:36.450
They can test positive for lead
poisoning, draw the attention

00:22:36.450 --> 00:22:39.110
of child protective
services, the police.

00:22:39.110 --> 00:22:42.320
"Kids cause us headache," is
what one landlord told me.

00:22:42.320 --> 00:22:46.810
Family discrimination is illegal,
but we know from studies that many

00:22:46.810 --> 00:22:50.610
of us don't even recognize that
as a kind of discrimination.

00:22:51.830 --> 00:22:57.480
So after that eviction, Arlene
started to unravel a little bit.

00:22:57.480 --> 00:23:01.690
She told me, "It's like
I got a curse on me.

00:23:01.690 --> 00:23:04.190
It won't stop for nothing.

00:23:04.190 --> 00:23:08.230
Sometimes I feel my body
trembling or shaking.

00:23:08.230 --> 00:23:10.830
I'm tired but I can't sleep.

00:23:10.830 --> 00:23:12.410
I'm fixing to have
a nervous breakdown.

00:23:12.410 --> 00:23:14.680
My body's trying to shut down."

00:23:14.680 --> 00:23:19.940
I recently published a
study that show that moms

00:23:19.940 --> 00:23:25.740 position:56%
who get evicted experience higher
rates of depression two years later.

00:23:25.740 --> 00:23:27.950
It sticks with you.

00:23:27.950 --> 00:23:31.690
And we know that between
2005 and 2010,

00:23:31.690 --> 00:23:34.910
years where housing costs were
soaring around our country,

00:23:34.910 --> 00:23:36.500
something else was going up to

00:23:36.500 --> 00:23:39.280
and those were suicides
attributed to eviction.

00:23:39.280 --> 00:23:42.610
They doubled during
that five-year timespan.

00:23:42.610 --> 00:23:51.720
Arlene told me, "Just
my soul is messed up.

00:23:51.720 --> 00:23:53.460
I wish my life were different.

00:23:53.460 --> 00:23:59.410
I wish that when I be an old lady,
I can sit back and look at my kids

00:23:59.410 --> 00:24:03.490
and they be grown and
they, you know,

00:24:03.490 --> 00:24:06.980
become something, something
more than me.

00:24:06.980 --> 00:24:10.760
And we'll all be together
and be laughing.

00:24:10.760 --> 00:24:14.970
We'll be remembering stuff like
this and be laughing at it."

00:24:27.040 --> 00:24:30.090
The home is the center of life.

00:24:30.090 --> 00:24:34.400
It's our refuge from work,

00:24:34.400 --> 00:24:37.930
the pressures of school,
Minnesota streets.

00:24:39.870 --> 00:24:42.300
We say at home, we're ourselves.

00:24:42.300 --> 00:24:44.390 position:56%
Everywhere else, we're someone else.

00:24:44.390 --> 00:24:50.120
At home, we remove our masks.

00:24:50.120 --> 00:24:51.870
In languages spoken
all over the world,

00:24:51.870 --> 00:24:55.290
the word for home encompasses
not just shelter but warmth

00:24:55.290 --> 00:25:00.350
and family, community, the womb.

00:25:00.350 --> 00:25:03.630
The ancient Egyptian
hieroglyph for home,

00:25:03.630 --> 00:25:06.070
it was the same one for mother.

00:25:07.730 --> 00:25:10.210
So eviction causes loss.

00:25:10.210 --> 00:25:13.900
Families lose not only their
homes, but often their schools,

00:25:13.900 --> 00:25:16.240
their community, your stuff.

00:25:16.240 --> 00:25:18.730
It takes a good amount of time
and money to establish a home.

00:25:18.730 --> 00:25:21.830
An eviction can delete all that.

00:25:21.830 --> 00:25:26.520 position:56%
An eviction comes with this blemish,
which can cause you not to move

00:25:26.520 --> 00:25:28.720
into a safe neighborhood
and to decent housing,

00:25:28.720 --> 00:25:31.210
it can also prevent you from
moving into public housing,

00:25:31.210 --> 00:25:32.890
because many of our
public housing authorities,

00:25:32.890 --> 00:25:35.830
even though they don't have
to, count eviction as a blemish

00:25:35.830 --> 00:25:37.920
or a strike against an application,

00:25:37.920 --> 00:25:40.330
which means we're systematically
denying housing help

00:25:40.330 --> 00:25:42.220
to families that need it most.

00:25:42.220 --> 00:25:45.850
So we push those families into slum
housing and into bad neighborhoods.

00:25:45.850 --> 00:25:48.560
We have a study that shows
that eviction causes job loss.

00:25:48.560 --> 00:25:51.110
I don't know if any of y'all
in this room have been evicted,

00:25:51.110 --> 00:25:53.050
but if you have, you know why.

00:25:53.050 --> 00:25:55.820
It's such a consuming,
stressful, drawn-out event.

00:25:55.820 --> 00:25:58.390
It can cause you to make mistakes
at work, lose your footing

00:25:58.390 --> 00:26:01.080 position:56%
in the labor market, and then
there's the effect that eviction has

00:26:01.080 --> 00:26:03.000
on your soul, like
Arlene would put it.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:04.830
Your mental health.

00:26:04.830 --> 00:26:07.100
Now, I think when we add all
that up, we have to conclude

00:26:07.100 --> 00:26:10.960
that evictions, which used
to be rare in this country,

00:26:10.960 --> 00:26:15.210
which used to draw crowds, they're
not just a condition of poverty.

00:26:15.210 --> 00:26:16.510
They're a cause of it too.

00:26:16.510 --> 00:26:18.090
They're making things worse
and they're leaving a deep

00:26:18.090 --> 00:26:20.050
and jagged scar on
the next generation,

00:26:20.050 --> 00:26:24.020
which means we can't fix poverty
in America without fixing housing.

00:26:24.020 --> 00:26:27.450
So how do we fix it?

00:26:27.450 --> 00:26:30.960
So imagine if every family
in this country had a decent,

00:26:30.960 --> 00:26:32.450
affordable place to leave.

00:26:32.450 --> 00:26:35.300
If Arlene didn't have to give 80
percent of her income to rent,

00:26:35.300 --> 00:26:38.910
she could keep her kids fed and
clothed and off the streets.

00:26:38.910 --> 00:26:40.460
We know from previous research

00:26:40.460 --> 00:26:43.330
that when families finally receive
a housing voucher after years

00:26:43.330 --> 00:26:46.660
and years on the waiting list, when
they finally receive this ticket

00:26:46.660 --> 00:26:49.160
that allows them to pay only 30
percent of their income on rent,

00:26:49.160 --> 00:26:52.380
instead of 60 or 70, they
do one consistent thing

00:26:52.380 --> 00:26:54.270
with their freed-up income.

00:26:54.270 --> 00:26:57.640
They take it to the grocery store.

00:26:57.640 --> 00:27:02.870
They buy more food and their kids
become stronger and less anemic.

00:27:02.870 --> 00:27:05.050
And they work.

00:27:05.050 --> 00:27:07.530
For the lucky minority
of poor families

00:27:07.530 --> 00:27:09.220
that benefit from them today.

00:27:09.220 --> 00:27:12.170
But the vast majority of our
pour families aren't so lucky,

00:27:12.170 --> 00:27:15.960 position:56%
and their kids, with names like Jori
and Jafar, aren't getting enough

00:27:15.960 --> 00:27:19.300
to eat because the rent eats first.

00:27:19.300 --> 00:27:22.490
And, like, if we can't afford the
freedoms our country offers us

00:27:22.490 --> 00:27:25.740
without a roof over our
head, like basic stuff,

00:27:25.740 --> 00:27:28.300
the freedom to better ourselves,
to protect our children,

00:27:28.300 --> 00:27:32.340
to be part of a community, then
shouldn't access to a decent,

00:27:32.340 --> 00:27:35.980
affordable home be part of what
it means to be an American?

00:27:35.980 --> 00:27:37.280
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:27:37.280 --> 00:27:39.080
&gt;&gt; We've affirmed --

00:27:39.080 --> 00:27:46.080
[ Applause ]

00:27:46.080 --> 00:27:50.260 position:56%
We've affirmed provision and old age
and access to 12 years of education

00:27:50.260 --> 00:27:54.400
and basic nutrition to be rights
in this country because we believe

00:27:54.400 --> 00:27:58.070 position:56%
that human flourishing and vitality
are impossible without those things.

00:27:58.070 --> 00:28:02.100
There is not an argument that says
that you can go without housing

00:28:02.100 --> 00:28:04.490
and still flourish and
be economically mobile.

00:28:04.490 --> 00:28:08.390
Housing should be a right in this
country and the reason is simple.

00:28:08.390 --> 00:28:12.030
Without stable shelter,
everything else falls apart.

00:28:12.030 --> 00:28:13.330
So then the question becomes, well,

00:28:13.330 --> 00:28:15.090
how do we deliver on
that obligation?

00:28:15.090 --> 00:28:18.670
And there's a lot of
good news here actually.

00:28:18.670 --> 00:28:20.060
There's a lot of good news.

00:28:20.060 --> 00:28:23.030
I mean, just a few generations
ago, there were slums in our cities

00:28:23.030 --> 00:28:25.600
and babies were dying
of tuberculosis

00:28:25.600 --> 00:28:28.740
and there were outhouses in the
middle of Philadelphia when some

00:28:28.740 --> 00:28:30.200
of y'all were still alive.

00:28:30.200 --> 00:28:33.150
We took on a battle with
the slum and we won.

00:28:33.150 --> 00:28:36.050
We won. And I'll be
the first to admit,

00:28:36.050 --> 00:28:38.020
and I think the book is pretty
clear out about this fact,

00:28:38.020 --> 00:28:40.180 position:56%
that we still have a long way to go.

00:28:40.180 --> 00:28:42.710
When I lived in the trailer park,
I didn't have hot water for most

00:28:42.710 --> 00:28:45.090
of the time, and I told the
landlord, like, "I am a writer.

00:28:45.090 --> 00:28:47.250
I'm going to write about
you and your trailer park."

00:28:47.250 --> 00:28:49.490
[ Laughter ]

00:28:49.490 --> 00:28:53.180
So imagine what my
neighbors had to endure.

00:28:53.180 --> 00:28:56.120
But there's no arguing that
we haven't made huge steps

00:28:56.120 --> 00:28:58.130
in the right direction when
it comes to the quality

00:28:58.130 --> 00:29:00.110
of housing folks are
living in today.

00:29:00.110 --> 00:29:01.990
It's just an important
thing to recognize.

00:29:01.990 --> 00:29:04.360 position:56%
Because sometimes when you talk
about poverty, the problem can be --

00:29:04.360 --> 00:29:06.030
fell so depressing and
feel so entrenched.

00:29:06.030 --> 00:29:10.300
It can feel like, "We fought the
war on poverty and nothing works."

00:29:10.300 --> 00:29:11.670
And that's just empirically false.

00:29:11.670 --> 00:29:14.310
When we want to take on
big problems as a country,

00:29:14.310 --> 00:29:16.420
we have come up with big solutions.

00:29:16.420 --> 00:29:19.690
I also just take a lot of heart
that there's organizations all

00:29:19.690 --> 00:29:22.990
around this country just putting in
work, driving down eviction rates,

00:29:22.990 --> 00:29:26.000
preserving affordable housing,
fighting family homelessness.

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:28.730
So you can go to this website that
we've started called just shelter,

00:29:28.730 --> 00:29:32.290
which amplifies that work, and
you can click on DC or Baltimore,

00:29:32.290 --> 00:29:35.520
Virginia, wherever you call
home, and you can figure out,

00:29:35.520 --> 00:29:37.440
"Who's working on this
problem in my own backyard?"

00:29:37.440 --> 00:29:40.290
You can learn more about what it
looks like in your own community.

00:29:40.290 --> 00:29:43.960
Maybe you can get plugged in
with your time or your money.

00:29:43.960 --> 00:29:45.440
So what's the bigger picture?

00:29:45.440 --> 00:29:48.240
A problem as big as the
affordable housing crisis calls

00:29:48.240 --> 00:29:49.540
for a big solution.

00:29:49.540 --> 00:29:52.710
We are bleeding out and it
would be disingenuous of me

00:29:52.710 --> 00:29:56.260
to stand here before you and
say a band-aid fix will do it.

00:29:56.260 --> 00:29:57.560
Because it won't.

00:29:57.560 --> 00:29:59.220
We need real bold political
leadership here.

00:29:59.220 --> 00:30:04.330
We need real moral vision here, so
one idea that would make a dream

00:30:04.330 --> 00:30:08.110
of affordable housing, a dream of a
house for every American a reality,

00:30:08.110 --> 00:30:09.980
would be to take a program
that we already have

00:30:09.980 --> 00:30:13.010
that works pretty darn well, the
Affordable Housing Voucher Program,

00:30:13.010 --> 00:30:16.980
and expand it to everyone
below the poverty line.

00:30:16.980 --> 00:30:18.650
So the idea is super simple.

00:30:18.650 --> 00:30:20.110
It's not even my idea.

00:30:20.110 --> 00:30:23.880
You take this program, and if
you fall below the poverty line,

00:30:23.880 --> 00:30:25.180
you qualify for it.

00:30:25.180 --> 00:30:27.600
And you get a voucher and you
can live anywhere you want,

00:30:27.600 --> 00:30:30.600
as long as your housing isn't
too expensive or too shoddy,

00:30:30.600 --> 00:30:32.460
and instead of paying
60 or 70 percent

00:30:32.460 --> 00:30:34.570
of your income on housing,
you pay 30.

00:30:34.570 --> 00:30:36.340
The voucher covers the rest.

00:30:36.340 --> 00:30:39.550
That would fundamentally change
the face of poverty in America.

00:30:39.550 --> 00:30:41.480
That would make evictions
rare again.

00:30:41.480 --> 00:30:43.630
That would drive down
family homelessness.

00:30:43.630 --> 00:30:46.280 position:56%
Families finally would receive that,

00:30:46.280 --> 00:30:48.920
that you feel when you're only
paying 30 percent of your income

00:30:48.920 --> 00:30:52.780
on housing, and be able to
buy enough food and save.

00:30:52.780 --> 00:30:56.160
So there's two questions
here that we might ask.

00:30:56.160 --> 00:30:59.950
One, would that be a
disincentive to work?

00:30:59.950 --> 00:31:02.020
It's a fair question.

00:31:02.020 --> 00:31:03.960
We in the research community
have spent a lot of time

00:31:03.960 --> 00:31:06.470
on that question, and there
are some studies that show

00:31:06.470 --> 00:31:08.570
that when families
receive housing assistance,

00:31:08.570 --> 00:31:12.070
they also experience a slight
reduction in work hours.

00:31:12.070 --> 00:31:13.720
I think they want to just
spend a little bit more time

00:31:13.720 --> 00:31:15.330
with their kids.

00:31:15.330 --> 00:31:17.770
There are way more studies that
don't find any relationship

00:31:17.770 --> 00:31:19.070
between those two things.

00:31:19.070 --> 00:31:21.340
Nerds like me call it
a null relationship.

00:31:21.340 --> 00:31:26.610 position:56%
And I think the status quo is a much
bigger threat to self-sufficiency

00:31:26.610 --> 00:31:29.400
and work than any affordable
housing program could be.

00:31:29.400 --> 00:31:32.480
I mean, families are crushed
by the high cost of housing.

00:31:32.480 --> 00:31:35.620
They can't afford community
college classes or job training,

00:31:35.620 --> 00:31:38.070
so they can get plugged in in
a better place in the economy.

00:31:38.070 --> 00:31:40.540
A lot of them can't afford to stay

00:31:40.540 --> 00:31:42.640
in one place long enough
to just hold down a job.

00:31:42.640 --> 00:31:46.540 position:56%
And just think of all, like, the
brainpower and talent and creativity

00:31:46.540 --> 00:31:50.890 position:56%
that we just squander because we ask
someone like Arlene to spend so much

00:31:50.890 --> 00:31:53.590
of hers trying to figure out
how she's going to make rent

00:31:53.590 --> 00:31:56.650 position:56%
from one month to the next, or where
she's going to live after her kids

00:31:56.650 --> 00:32:00.560
and her are inevitably,
predictably, evicted.

00:32:00.560 --> 00:32:04.480
Poverty reduces people
born for better things.

00:32:04.480 --> 00:32:07.140
Arlene didn't want some small life.

00:32:07.140 --> 00:32:10.430
She didn't want to gain the
system and eek out an existence.

00:32:10.430 --> 00:32:12.970
In fact, when she finally
found stable housing,

00:32:12.970 --> 00:32:16.190
the first thing she did was
start applying for jobs.

00:32:16.190 --> 00:32:18.670
She wanted to work and thrive
and contribute, and a stable,

00:32:18.670 --> 00:32:21.400
affordable home would give
folks like Arlene a shot

00:32:21.400 --> 00:32:23.670
at realizing their full potential.

00:32:23.670 --> 00:32:29.180
So the second question
is, can we afford it?

00:32:29.180 --> 00:32:33.940
It sounds kind of expensive, a
universal housing voucher program.

00:32:33.940 --> 00:32:37.250
It's totally expensive.

00:32:37.250 --> 00:32:40.410
We can totally afford it.

00:32:40.410 --> 00:32:43.810 position:56%
So Bipartisan Policy Center
crunched the numbers a few years ago

00:32:43.810 --> 00:32:46.630
and they found that the kind
of program that I'm advocating

00:32:46.630 --> 00:32:50.380
for today would cost us an
additional 22 billion dollars

00:32:50.380 --> 00:32:51.680
a year.

00:32:51.680 --> 00:32:52.980
22 billion dollars.

00:32:52.980 --> 00:32:54.280
Raw number.

00:32:54.280 --> 00:32:56.400 position:56%
Doesn't account for the savings we'd
recoup by driving down homelessness,

00:32:56.400 --> 00:32:58.910
rates of depression, rates of
asthma, things we already pay for,

00:32:58.910 --> 00:33:00.210
because there's two ways to spend.

00:33:00.210 --> 00:33:02.280
We can spend smart
or we spend stupid.

00:33:02.280 --> 00:33:04.860
That's just the raw number.

00:33:04.860 --> 00:33:08.380
Now, 22 billion dollars
is not a small figure,

00:33:08.380 --> 00:33:10.340
but it's well within our capacity.

00:33:10.340 --> 00:33:12.410
We have the money.

00:33:12.410 --> 00:33:15.370
We just made decisions
about how to spend it.

00:33:15.370 --> 00:33:19.220
So, every year in this country,
homeowner tax subsidies,

00:33:19.220 --> 00:33:23.020
especially the mortgage
interest deduction, they far,

00:33:23.020 --> 00:33:26.890
far outpace direct housing
assistance to the needy.

00:33:26.890 --> 00:33:30.100
We already have a universal
housing program.

00:33:30.100 --> 00:33:32.560
It's an entitlement.

00:33:32.560 --> 00:33:34.440
It's just not for poor people.

00:33:34.440 --> 00:33:40.170
So the year that Arlene was evicted
from 13th Street, we, as a nation,

00:33:40.170 --> 00:33:43.340
spent about 41 billion dollars
on direct housing assistance

00:33:43.340 --> 00:33:46.590
to the needy, things like
public housing in Section 8.

00:33:46.590 --> 00:33:49.720
That same year, we spent
about 171 billion dollars

00:33:49.720 --> 00:33:51.440
on homeowner tax subsidies.

00:33:51.440 --> 00:33:55.980
That number, 171 billion
dollars, that was equivalent

00:33:55.980 --> 00:33:59.270
to the entire budgets of the
Departments of Education,

00:33:59.270 --> 00:34:06.480
Veteran Affairs, Homeland Security,
Justice and Agriculture, combined.

00:34:06.480 --> 00:34:09.070
It's a rather large number.

00:34:09.070 --> 00:34:12.660
Most of that benefit goes to
families with six-figure incomes,

00:34:12.660 --> 00:34:14.980
because if your income is
bigger, your mortgage is bigger

00:34:14.980 --> 00:34:17.200
so your deduction is too.

00:34:17.200 --> 00:34:20.300
Most white families in America
own a home with a mortgage.

00:34:20.300 --> 00:34:23.130
Most Latino and African-American
families do not.

00:34:23.130 --> 00:34:26.780
It is hard to think
of a social policy

00:34:26.780 --> 00:34:31.200
that more unblushingly amplifies
our racial and economic inequality

00:34:31.200 --> 00:34:33.180
than our current housing
policy does.

00:34:33.180 --> 00:34:36.460
So if we want to spend the bulk of
our public dollars on the affluent,

00:34:36.460 --> 00:34:39.910
at least when it comes to housing,
let's just be honest about that.

00:34:39.910 --> 00:34:41.210
Let's just own up to that.

00:34:41.210 --> 00:34:43.030
Let's just be like, "Yes, this
is the kind of country you want.

00:34:43.030 --> 00:34:44.680
This is our social contract."

00:34:44.680 --> 00:34:47.040
Instead of repeating this
lie that the richest country

00:34:47.040 --> 00:34:49.610
on the planet can't
afford to do more.

00:34:49.610 --> 00:34:51.510
If poverty persists --

00:34:51.510 --> 00:35:00.280
[ Applause ]

00:35:00.280 --> 00:35:02.110
You know, if poverty
persists in America,

00:35:02.110 --> 00:35:04.460
it's not because we lack resources.

00:35:04.460 --> 00:35:10.910
We lack something else.

00:35:10.910 --> 00:35:12.570
Okay. So it's one idea.

00:35:12.570 --> 00:35:13.880
Like, let others come.

00:35:13.880 --> 00:35:17.190
You know, one city has to
build, another has to destroy.

00:35:17.190 --> 00:35:18.710
Our cities are different.

00:35:18.710 --> 00:35:21.810
You know, what works in DC is
going to fail in Milwaukee.

00:35:21.810 --> 00:35:25.890
LA needs a completely different
thing than Birmingham does.

00:35:25.890 --> 00:35:28.460
But I think whatever our
way out of this mess,

00:35:28.460 --> 00:35:30.160
one thing for me is certain.

00:35:30.160 --> 00:35:36.700
Like, this degree of inequality
and this level of social suffering

00:35:36.700 --> 00:35:40.910
and this just, like,
blunting of human potential,

00:35:40.910 --> 00:35:44.230
this cold denial of,
like, a basic human need,

00:35:44.230 --> 00:35:49.060
I don't -- like, this isn't us.

00:35:49.060 --> 00:35:52.450
Like, this doesn't have to be us.

00:35:52.450 --> 00:35:55.500
By no American value is
this situation justified.

00:35:55.500 --> 00:35:58.720
There's no ethical code, there's
no holy teaching, there's no piece

00:35:58.720 --> 00:36:00.560
of scripture that could be summoned

00:36:00.560 --> 00:36:02.780
to defend what we've allowed
our country to become.

00:36:02.780 --> 00:36:04.580
Thank you.

00:36:04.580 --> 00:36:31.660
[ Applause ]

00:36:31.660 --> 00:36:33.320
We have time for questions.

00:36:33.320 --> 00:36:37.450
Thanks, sound guys, for getting
through that technical difficulty.

00:36:37.450 --> 00:36:39.120
It's really great to
see you guys up here.

00:36:39.120 --> 00:36:41.760
Thank you so much.

