00:37:21.200 --> 00:37:23.630
But I think just spending
enough time with folks

00:37:23.630 --> 00:37:29.350
and really living there
helped do it, yeah.

00:37:29.350 --> 00:37:34.060
&gt;&gt; This is a great book and I love
the combination of quantitative

00:37:34.060 --> 00:37:37.350
and qualitative materials
that you brought together.

00:37:37.350 --> 00:37:40.080
But I'd like to go back to
your last comments here.

00:37:40.080 --> 00:37:42.840
Could you kind of recreate
the historical context

00:37:42.840 --> 00:37:46.770
in which the original housing
voucher program came about?

00:37:46.770 --> 00:37:50.760
And are those replicable
in the near future?

00:37:50.760 --> 00:37:52.740
And it's not a negative question,

00:37:52.740 --> 00:37:55.100
but just how did it come
about, first of all?

00:37:55.100 --> 00:37:56.880
&gt;&gt; Matthew Desmond: Negative
questions are good too, you know?

00:37:56.880 --> 00:37:58.910
Negative questions are good.

00:37:58.910 --> 00:38:01.220
And so, but I don't see
it as a negative question.

00:38:01.220 --> 00:38:02.950
That's a really important point.

00:38:02.950 --> 00:38:08.040 position:56%
So the story of public policy toward
housing is often a story riddled

00:38:08.040 --> 00:38:11.020
with, like, really big mistakes,
or that's how it's read anyways.

00:38:11.020 --> 00:38:13.910
So, you know, we had a giant, like,

00:38:13.910 --> 00:38:16.810
social experiment called
public housing, which was going

00:38:16.810 --> 00:38:18.490
to replace our sum communities.

00:38:18.490 --> 00:38:23.020
And we said, "Why don't we
build giant towers in the middle

00:38:23.020 --> 00:38:25.280
of really poor, desolate
areas of our city?

00:38:25.280 --> 00:38:29.760
Pruitt-Igoe in St. Louis,
Robert Taylor homes in Chicago.

00:38:29.760 --> 00:38:31.410
And so we built these towers up,

00:38:31.410 --> 00:38:34.570
and the thing that we often
forget is, like, that was amazing.

00:38:34.570 --> 00:38:37.600 position:56%
Like, when you read the transcripts
of the first residents of those kind

00:38:37.600 --> 00:38:40.030
of public housing towers, they
were like, "This is incredible.

00:38:40.030 --> 00:38:41.770
This is like Christmas."

00:38:41.770 --> 00:38:43.070
But we defunded it.

00:38:43.070 --> 00:38:44.990
We gutted the funding and
soon, like, no one was picking

00:38:44.990 --> 00:38:46.930
up the trash and the
elevators weren't working.

00:38:46.930 --> 00:38:49.250
And if you were a family
that could move out, you did,

00:38:49.250 --> 00:38:53.020
and those towers descended into
incredibly concentrated poverty

00:38:53.020 --> 00:38:54.840
and sometimes even, like, chaos.

00:38:54.840 --> 00:38:57.840
You know, Pruitt-Igoe, these
giant towers in St. Louis,

00:38:57.840 --> 00:39:00.300
were destroyed 18 years
after they were erected.

00:39:00.300 --> 00:39:05.200
So from those ashes, the Public
Housing Voucher System started

00:39:05.200 --> 00:39:10.170
to emerge, and it has become the
main way we provide affordable

00:39:10.170 --> 00:39:11.910
housing to families today.

00:39:11.910 --> 00:39:14.960
It's not a perfect system, but
there's no study in the world

00:39:14.960 --> 00:39:19.550
that shows that you can offer
families equal quality housing

00:39:19.550 --> 00:39:22.140
for a lesser cost than you
can through a voucher program.

00:39:22.140 --> 00:39:24.500
So the problem that I always
[inaudible] with when I was trying

00:39:24.500 --> 00:39:26.490
to conclude this book,
like, what policy do I want

00:39:26.490 --> 00:39:29.000
to get behind, is the
problem of scale.

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:31.440
There's all sorts of awesome
ways we can address this problem,

00:39:31.440 --> 00:39:33.490
but if we want to address
it at scale,

00:39:33.490 --> 00:39:39.220
the voucher program's
the best way to do so.

00:39:39.220 --> 00:39:40.820
&gt;&gt; [Inaudible] question.

00:39:40.820 --> 00:39:44.340
You made a distinction between
men who are incarcerated and women

00:39:44.340 --> 00:39:47.510
who lose their homes, and I just
wanted to point out that the rate

00:39:47.510 --> 00:39:52.450
of female incarceration is rising
exponentially in the US right now.

00:39:52.450 --> 00:39:57.590
That aside, what could you
tell me about the landlords

00:39:57.590 --> 00:40:01.690
that would surprise me, given my
sense that these are, you know,

00:40:01.690 --> 00:40:04.380
bad people or something like
-- what would, you know,

00:40:04.380 --> 00:40:07.460
something that would
make me feel differently?

00:40:07.460 --> 00:40:11.020
&gt;&gt; Matthew Desmond: I hope
the book does its best to try

00:40:11.020 --> 00:40:13.940
to capture both sides with
their full complexity,

00:40:13.940 --> 00:40:16.470
and I think it's way too easy,
you know, just to say, "Oh,

00:40:16.470 --> 00:40:17.770
these landlords are just greedy."

00:40:17.770 --> 00:40:19.070
Or, "Oh, these tenants are just
lazy," depending on where we fall

00:40:19.070 --> 00:40:20.370
in the political spectrum.

00:40:20.370 --> 00:40:21.670
You know, from the sidewalk
view, it's really hard.

00:40:21.670 --> 00:40:22.970
And so one thing that surprised
me was when I started this work,

00:40:22.970 --> 00:40:24.270
I was like, "Why would you buy
property on 13th Street and Keefe?"

00:40:24.270 --> 00:40:25.570
And when I finished this
work, I was like, "Oh,

00:40:25.570 --> 00:40:26.870
why wouldn't you do that?"

00:40:26.870 --> 00:40:28.170
Because you can make a lot of
money, quite a bit of money.

00:40:28.170 --> 00:40:29.470
And so, you know, the landlord of
the trailer park that I lived in,

00:40:29.470 --> 00:40:30.770
you know, he let me copy his
rent rolls, so I could account

00:40:30.770 --> 00:40:32.070
for vacancies and missed payments.

00:40:32.070 --> 00:40:33.370
I got his mortgage records,
I got his water bill,

00:40:33.370 --> 00:40:34.670
I got his trash collecting
records, I got his eviction costs.

00:40:34.670 --> 00:40:35.970
I'm telling you all this so
you believe me, that, you know,

00:40:35.970 --> 00:40:37.270
the landlord of, like,
the worst trailer park

00:40:37.270 --> 00:40:38.570
in the fourth worst
city of Milwaukee,

00:40:38.570 --> 00:40:39.870
which is 130-trailers big,

00:40:39.870 --> 00:40:41.170
takes home about 470,000
dollars a year after expenses.

00:40:41.170 --> 00:40:42.470
That, for me, changed the
way I think about poverty,

00:40:42.470 --> 00:40:43.800
because it means, like, poverty
isn't just about low incomes.

00:40:43.800 --> 00:40:45.100
It's also about extractive markets.

00:40:45.100 --> 00:40:46.400
You know, there are winners and
losers, and there are losers

00:40:46.400 --> 00:40:47.700
because there are winners.

00:40:47.700 --> 00:40:49.000
And that point isn't
just about landlords.

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:50.300
I think that point is about a
lot of us in the room today,

00:40:50.300 --> 00:40:51.600 position:56%
including things like our housing
and our schools and our tax records.

00:40:51.600 --> 00:40:52.900
&gt;&gt; Hey, Matt.

00:40:52.900 --> 00:40:54.200
Thank you for this
great, great book.

00:40:54.200 --> 00:40:55.500
I wanted to say a quick question
about the writing of the book.

00:40:55.500 --> 00:40:56.800
Why did you choose not to
include yourself in the book,

00:40:56.800 --> 00:40:58.100
despite doing the same kind of
immersive journalism as a, say,

00:40:58.100 --> 00:40:59.400
a Nickel and Dimed or
something like that?

00:40:59.400 --> 00:41:00.700
Did you give it thought?

00:41:00.700 --> 00:41:02.000
Did you think it would
change the story?

00:41:02.000 --> 00:41:03.300
Or why aren't you a
character in the book?

00:41:03.300 --> 00:41:04.600
&gt;&gt; Matthew Desmond: I
gave it a ton of thought.

00:41:04.600 --> 00:41:05.900
You know, Nickel and Dimed
is a first person because,

00:41:05.900 --> 00:41:07.200
like, that's the idea.

00:41:07.200 --> 00:41:08.500
Like, I went and I did this.

00:41:08.500 --> 00:41:09.800
And I -- it is a form of immersive
journalism, or ethnography,

00:41:09.800 --> 00:41:11.100
but it's also -- I didn't
want the reader to look at me.

00:41:11.100 --> 00:41:12.400
I didn't want the reader
to care about me.

00:41:12.400 --> 00:41:13.700
Like, I am not the
important thing in the story.

00:41:13.700 --> 00:41:15.000
Arlene and Crystal and
Vanetta and Scott and Lorraine,

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:16.300
they're the important
people in the story.

00:41:16.300 --> 00:41:17.600 position:56%
And so I didn't want, when something
was happening, you thinking,

00:41:17.600 --> 00:41:18.900
"How's Matt dealing with this?"

00:41:18.900 --> 00:41:20.200
Or, "Where is Matt in the story?"

00:41:20.200 --> 00:41:21.500
I didn't want you to care,
and so I erased myself.

00:41:21.500 --> 00:41:22.800
And I write about, like,
the tradeoffs of that kind

00:41:22.800 --> 00:41:24.100
of approach in the end of the book.

00:41:24.100 --> 00:41:25.400
I'm being told by the bosses
that I have to wrap it up.

00:41:25.400 --> 00:41:26.700
Thank you guys so much --

00:41:26.700 --> 00:41:28.000
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:29.300
&gt;&gt; For coming.

00:41:29.300 --> 00:41:30.600
Thank you.

